Continuing SE corner of dog park (NE corner of park). What appears to be just the second record of S. r. ruber for San Diego County. From Unitt (2004): "The one specimen of ruber, from 5 miles northeast of Lakeside (N14) 9 November 1957 (SDNHM 30061), is the southernmost of this largely nonmigratory subspecies. Sphyrapicus r. ruber differs from daggetti mainly in its brighter red head (in fresh plumage scarlet rather than crimson), less extensive white head stripe, and smaller yellow-tinged spots on the back."

Observation Details: Wonderful looks, textbook example (with Sibley's illustration being the textbook) of northern variant, all red head, white spot top of bill, gold-spotted rows on back, no evidence of hybridization. (Picture attached.) Bird was lazily working sap galleries on large maple tree about 300' northwest of the large pavilion which is just north (across parking lot and up the hill) of the circular softball complex.  Met up with Dave Wheeler later in the afternoon looking at ducks on the Jordan, we took him and his son Petey  to the park to share the bird and he confirmed i.d.   Have many pics and videos, bird was oblivious to us on the ground right under the tree and will likely be there tomorrow for easy confirmation.  What a wonderful start to the New Year!

Media notes: red of head extends well onto yellow breast - short white malar on otherwise red head with a few black auricular feathers is therefore the northern subsp.  ruber; daggetti or southern subspecies has variable length but always much longer white malar extending often through auriculars to become a moustachial stripe (unlike this very short white malar stripe of ruber) and usually has lighter red tones on face; daggetti also has more white and less yellow on breast; red of daggetti less intense - sexes not separable in this species from photos. Hybrid RBSA x RNSA photos available for comparison on TX and AZ sites.
Observation Details: sapsucker with complete red head except for black auricular patches and short white malar with red continuing below nape and onto breast where it is defined from yellow breast. Black back with faint white streaks and large white wing patch. Separated from southern subspecies, daggetti, by the shorter white malar (see photos). Sexes not separable in field. Found on 21 December 2017 by David Tonnessen who was surveying for sapsuckers in non-native conifers in the area.

Media notes: Red-breasted Sapsucker, ruber subspecies, Lake Sherwood, CA - 27 Feb 2022
Observation Details: This bird has been around for months, but the subspecies was overlooked. The ruber subspecies is very rare this far south. This is at least the third one in the Santa Barbara/Ventura Counties region this winter so there must be some abnormal movement this winter. Compared to the more expected daggetti subspecies, this bird had a deeper scarlet-red head, richer yellow belly, whitish line from the top of the base of the bill to the front of the eye, and a black back with two narrow rows of goldish-colored spots.

Showed no hesitation or fear when we approached within about 35-40 feet or so.  Looked quite content taking care of his business.  Using his tail for vertical support as evident in the pictures.  Four toes.  Left the bird still tending to his sap wells.  Way cool bird!  Continuing bird seen by many.  See linked pictures...

Media notes: Beautiful Male--rather shy. Gleans insects from gaps in Fir Trees. When tapping he is not noisy or aggressive, just enough pressure to make a hole in the surface of bark, for sap to flow. This attracts insects which Sapsuckers then eat. Hummingbirds are also attracted to these sap holes for the same reason re: protein.
Observation Details: Watched this beautiful bird for quite awhile--managed to get a quick pic. Next day, took pics of holes in Douglas Firs which he makes to attract insects re: sap flow. From what we understand, this does not hurt the trees as it is mainly surface damage, much like Maples being tapped.

First heard loud drumming on the large dead cottonwood (about 9:30 a.m) then it moved to the large hackberry where it spent the next half hour attending dripping sapsucker wells and creating new ones. Head red with red extending down onto breast. Black smudgy patch on the auriculars and black lores. Didn't appear to have any black on the back of the head. Short white moustachial stripe, indicating northern subspecies, but back had two rows of white markings, no apparent yellow or gold spots, indicating southern subspecies. Intergrade?

Continuing.   This sapsucker is very interesting … I see a ruber head, being red-helmeted with red bleeding over the white border, and the red being fairly bright. However, I see a daggetti’s excessive back patterning and the back spots being more off-white vs yellow like on a ruber. Another interesting feature, is that the red from its head bleeds past its nape and onto its upper back. I am fascinated by this subject, and feedback is ways appreciated!!  0919 -  Observed working a Tipu approx. here (33.7065371, -118.0028552) by Loren’s Ditch. Silent and solo.  Update (2/3) : Tom W and I had a discussion, confirming this subspecies as the "daggetti" subspecies. I observed the nest site for an hour or so, from a responsible distance (seated on the ground, tucked in and mostly hidden between two small D. Fir trees), which didn't appear in any way to disturb the very busy adults.  I observed two complete nest exchanges where the adult male and female changed places, one going inside the nest hole to care for the young, the other going out foraging for food for the young. Foraging cycles averaged about 5 minutes between feedings.  Nest exchanges averaged about every 20 or 25 minutes.  At each nest exchange, one of the adults would fly out with a fecal sac, drop it on the ground 20 more feet from the nest tree, then return to a dead limb and use it to clean the fecal matter from their bill, by swiping their bill from side to side on the limb.  Very fascinating to watch them.

Media notes: Stewart Fletcher, Photographer; RBSA - NOT a daggetti southern subspecies
Observation Details: visual 1 adult at sap wells in two different hardwood trees, Connie H J shows us the two examples of tree trunk sap-well grid shapes in both round and square; visual 2 adults, a pair seen concurrently at tree cavity, bringing food into a cavity filled with nestlings (can hear continuous food-begging nestlings within cavity) in a ponderosa pine snag at top of Mill Cr canyon  Visual of a 4th adult photographed with food in bill and part of a front yard pair and a photograph of it with mate by Stewart Fletcher ---- It is NOT a daggetti subspecies by May 29, 2023 confirmation from woodpecker specialist, Stephen Shunk, who shares, "CJ, I don't think you can call that bird a daggetti.  The southern daggetti subspecies shows at least SOME semblance of a white supercilium, and it is absent in this bird. There is no noticeable white above the eye.   The bigger issue here is that introgression occurs between the two subspecies--we know this--and since daggetti is more prone to movement, the intergrades may also be more prone to wandering than the pure S.r. ruber. With the exception of far western individuals, IDing RBSA to subspecies in Oregon is very problematic, especially on the eastern slope of the Cascades; this bird was near the OR/WA border and east of the Cascades. The prudent thing is to record this bird as RBSA, with no subspecies distinction.   The compulsion to assign an ID to birds gets in the way of our understanding and appreciation of their genetics, including systematics and taxonomy. We have to appreciate the complicated situation that occurs with RNSA and RBSA in the West, especially in the Cascades. Many hybrids and intergrades occur here, and it may take DNA to narrow an ID to species, let alone subspecies."  Stephen Shunk - steve@paradisebirding.com Paradise Birding & Naturalist Journeys www.paradisebirding.com & www.naturalistjourneys.com +1-541-408-1753  Photographs:  Linda Steider and Stewart Fletcher

Observation Details: I observed the nest site for an hour or so, from a responsible distance (seated on the ground, tucked in and mostly hidden between two small D. Fir trees), which didn't appear in any way to disturb the very busy adults.  I observed two complete nest exchanges where the adult male and female changed places, one going inside the nest hole to care for the young, the other going out foraging for food for the young. Foraging cycles averaged about 5 minutes between feedings.  Nest exchanges averaged about every 20 or 25 minutes.  At each nest exchange, one of the adults would fly out with a fecal sac, drop it on the ground 20 more feet from the nest tree, then return to a dead limb and use it to clean the fecal matter from their bill, by swiping their bill from side to side on the limb.  Very fascinating to watch them.

Media notes: Red-Breasted Sapsucker, probably Southern or daggetti subspecies. However, it is very difficult to tell apart this subspecies from the hybrid Red-Breasted x Red-Naped. This individual has very little red on it apart from the crown and throat, with some in the nape area. The distinctive white zig-zag line across its face with some black around it is perhaps more like the Red-Naped than the daggetti subspecies. But the photos match pretty well the daggetti illustration in Sibley Birds West.

Locality: Riverview Wildlife Refuge / Snohomish Wastewater Treatment Plant

Observation Details: Conservative estimate. I spent much of the day scanning pepper trees and pines for any sign of sapsuckers and lucked out on Red-breasted several times. It's more likely that I observed 6 or 7 sapsuckers, however it's feasible that I ran into some individuals more than once.   Most of the birds (about 3) were seen in the pepper tree grove just north and northwest of the tennis courts. They were seen far enough from each other that I determined they were individual birds. One of these 3 was calling for a brief period.   Another was seen along the round dirt trail at the far east end of the park, and at least one was moving between peppers and sycamores close to the entrance. The birds were generally most active and conspicuous between 8:30 and 10:00 am.   Surprisingly no other sapsucker species were identified while I was there, although I don't doubt that I missed several.

While I was watching the adult sapsuckers feeding their young,  an adult in photos 2 and 3 flew past the nest, and a few seconds later one of the chicks suddenly propelled itself out of the nest and flew to a nearby tree with the  adult.  Afterwards the other adult (probably) came back to the nest and seemed not to know the chick had flown off.  It was apparently the only chick in the nest.  An hour or more later as I left, I stopped and an adult stuck its head in the nest again as if looking for a chick.

Photo’s. Continuing on same pine tree as earlier reported. Location is at the pin for this checklist.   Sapsucker with predominately red head and red breast. I spent considerable time observing this bird as I tried to photograph it and cannot find any reason to ID it as anything but a RBSA. It has a fairly solid red crown and hind crown/nape, fairly solid red behind eye on auriculars, and a predominately rich red breast with no black in all good viewing angles [note: when viewing at steep upward angles there appears to be some darkness lying under the lower red breast feathers, but I believe this is just artifact of light (shadow) as when viewing with bins at close range at horizontal angles I can see no black underneath], yellow on belly, and two well-defined narrow bands of white spots on back (not extensive like in many/most RNSA’s) . Wings in all photo’s are tucked under puffed side feathers obscuring the white sapsucker bars on wings. After reviewing hundreds of photographs of daggetti RBSA I believe the black patterning on side of head and breast of this bird is well within normal variation for this subspecies. This identification  does not discount the possibility that this bird has some amount  of RNSA in it, but the lack of consistent and specific markers for hybrid (or my inability to pick them out on this bird) and that it generally appears much more RBSA-like make me chose this category for this bird.  Likely daggeti subspecies due to narrow bands of white spots (not yellowish of rubber) on back, some black on head and hind neck,  and noticeable white stripe below eye.   Thanks Dave T for the heads up on this bird, and the discussion of the difficulties and possibilities when trying to assign some of these sapsuckers..

Found by Ken Murphey earlier this week.  The bird has stayed in the general location preferring sap from holes drilled into a Gooding's Willow along the Santa Cruz river effluent.  The bird has been seen by many observers and I am sure it has been scrutinized for any hybridization.  In the field I began to worry that I was seeing some light flecking of black feathers loosely in the breast, but only while viewing the bird while it was in the shade.  When the bird is in the sun the breast appears bright red with no black feathers.  I also like the amount of red in the face specifically through the moustacial stripe.  I don't see many RBSAs hardly ever so I had to do some extra research at home and now am feeling better about calling it pure.  The bird was totally silent the whole time, even while being harassed by local Gila Woodpeckers.

Details originally submitted as Sapsucker sp.: Possibly a daggetti Red-breasted Sapsucker.  If not, then certainly a RBSA hybrid. I chased this bird with some doubts of it being a pure bird, and while field views and additional photos do suggest that it may be a pure bird, I still have some doubts.  The amount of retained juvenal body feathers (at least that's what I think they are) may point to some RNSA influence.  RBSA apparently lose all juvenal body feathers by Oct.  The nape appears to be clean red, which is good for RBSA.  Photos will be circulated, and hopefully people with more RBSA and hybrid experience will provide input.   Note: Accepted in 2013 as first NM record by NMBRC

Media notes: One of two Red-breasted Sapsuckers seen on this date photographed here by Curtis A. Marantz on 24 March 2017 at Lake Tamarisk, Desert Center, Riverside County, California.  This was the first of the two birds, seen here in trees near the Baptist church.
Observation Details: Given the rarity of Red-breasted Sapsuckers in the southern deserts we were rather surprised to see two different birds on this date, one with a somewhat bolder than expected moustachial stripe in the large tamarisk tree north of the Baptist Church and a cleaner bird in threes near the most southwestern yard on the property.  Apart from the extent of the moustachial stripe both bird appeared essentially identical.  Neither bird called and both were difficult to see well.  I managed to get a few mediocre photos of the first bird, but none of the second. Both bird were small to medium-sized woodpeckers with rounded crowns, stocky necks, plump bodies, relatively long wings and short tails.  Both bird also had medium-length bills that were almost as long as the head was wide, and which tapered from bases of medium-depth to pointed tips along straight culmens.  These birds both had mostly red heads, with the forehead, crown, and nape red and with no obvious band separating the crown and nape.  My impression was that both birds also had black around the eye and some on the auriculars, yet neither bird had any suggestion of a supercilium.  The bird near the church had a white moustachial that extended from the base of the upper mandible across the lower part of the face below the eye and extending to some degree to the corner of the throat however, the moustachial was broken by red clouding below the eye.  The throat and upper breast were again red and I noted no suggestion of a black border to the throat or an obvious breast-band.  The bird in the southwestern part of the property appeared similar in all respects with the exception that the moustachial stripe appeared to extend only from the base of the bill back to a pint under the eye before being cut off by red below the eye, and on this bird the moustachial did not reappear behind the eye, so the red of the throat blended into that of the auriculars behind the eye.  Both bird had the sides and flanks clouded with gray and whitish mottling and at least one of them (though I cannot now recall which one) had a bright yellow belly. Returning to the upperparts, both birds also had black backs with two braces of white clouding that separated the mantle and scapulars, which were more solidly black, and both birds had not only a white blaze along the leading edge of the wing, but also finer barring on the remiges and narrow edges to the primary tips exposed in the wingtip.  I further noted white edges to what appeared to be the inner rectrices and, as I recall, white barring on the other webs of the outers.  One the church bird I also noted at least some suggestion of white uppertail-coverts that had some black barring. I noted that the eyes were dark and the bills essentially black, but I cannot recall noting the color of the legs or feet on either bird.

Media notes: Presumed male as head colour darker than other parent.
Observation Details: Sapsucker activity has been increasing around the yard over the last few days and today we saw the first juvenile of the year in our yard.  Both parents attended the juvenile from time to time and re-drilled many of the holes in our birch tree.  The juvenile stayed in the birch for quite a bit of time, feeding at the sap holes but also being fed periodically by the parents.  Interestingly, the adults started drumming again today (they have not drummed for a number of weeks since territories were set up earlier this spring).  Perhaps they are reasserting ownership now that they have fledglings feeding i2n the area.

Bird was still most of the time and quiet.

This one totally shocked me. I was just going to start walking up the easement along the "canyon hole", and instead I walked slightly west about 100 yards to look down into an area that separates our community from Mountain View Estates just to our west. I often times see our resident male Vermilion Flycatcher, who has been seen every month since he was discovered on the December 2012 Christmas bird count in this area around a bunch of Pepper Trees.   Suddenly something much larger than the Vermilion Flycatcher and with even brighter red color popped in my view at the base of one of the Pepper Trees. I was shocked to quickly realize that it was a Woodpecker. I have never seen any woodpeckers in our Country Club before except for Northern Flickers.   I felt sorry for this woodpecker as he or she kept going from one Pepper Tree to the next, and even to a few Washingtonian Palm Trees trying to apparently get sap, or at least get sap holes made. I got plenty of pictures of him. Let me know if they show any evidence that he or she might be a hybrid bird versus a full Red-breasted Sapsucker as more than a few of the pictures seem to show some yellow tint to part of its belly.  A additional side note is as of 1-11-16, Riverside County Ebird expert moderator Curtis Marantz let me know that this bird has been looked at by at least 3 experts, including himself,  Kimball Garrett and John Dunn and has been identified as the very rare Northern subspecies of the Red-breasted Sapsucker, which per Curtis is very rare anywhere in Southern California.

Plump, squarish woodpecker clinging to side of pine. Blackish back with dirty white/ sooty gray spots on back. Sooty flanks.  Bird was first observed on east side of road in 3 Austrian/Scotch Pines on the east side of the road. Shortly after spotting it, it flew to an Austrian/Scotch Pine on the west side of and closest to the road. It's next stop was a set of cottonwoods directly to the north of the Austrian/Scotch Pine on the west side of the road. Finally, it flew northwest across the golf course to a somewhat distant row of conifers with an Austrian/Scotch pine as the south-western most of the trees (the others are a mix of spruces?). From there, it may have been seen flying to an unknown location.

Details originally submitted as Sapsucker sp.: Possibly a daggetti Red-breasted Sapsucker.  If not, then certainly a RBSA hybrid. I chased this bird with some doubts of it being a pure bird, and while field views and additional photos do suggest that it may be a pure bird, I still have some doubts.  The amount of retained juvenal body feathers (at least that's what I think they are) may point to some RNSA influence.  RBSA apparently lose all juvenal body feathers by Oct.  The nape appears to be clean red, which is good for RBSA.  Photos will be circulated, and hopefully people with more RBSA and hybrid experience will provide input.   Note: Accepted in 2013 as first NM record by NMBRC

Observation Details: Pics. Found yesterday by Tom H. Some discussion as to whether this is ssp. daggetti versus a hybrid RBSAxRNSA. This bird looks very much like the one shown in Lehman 1991, described as a female daggetti-type of RBSA, which can have prominent white malar and black cheek. Also consistent with description of daggetti-type RBSA as described by Shunk 2005 (which allows for white malar, smaller faint white stripe behind eye and black cheek). Extent and vibrancy of red and neat & narrow rows of light feathering on back suggest this as RBSA, though it is difficult to exclude RNSA genes in the ancestry for a bird with this appearance.

Continuing.   This sapsucker is very interesting … I see a ruber head, being red-helmeted with red bleeding over the white border, and the red being fairly bright. However, I see a daggetti’s excessive back patterning and the back spots being more off-white vs yellow like on a ruber. Another interesting feature, is that the red from its head bleeds past its nape and onto its upper back. I am fascinated by this subject, and feedback is ways appreciated!!  0919 -  Observed working a Tipu approx. here (33.7065371, -118.0028552) by Loren’s Ditch. Silent and solo.  Update (2/3) : Tom W and I had a discussion, confirming this subspecies as the "daggetti" subspecies. Thank you, Tom, for your wonderful insight into this interesting character!! :))

Media notes: RBSA adult at sap well tree photographed by Linda Steider
Observation Details: visual 1 adult at sap wells in two different hardwood trees, Connie H J shows us the two examples of tree trunk sap-well grid shapes in both round and square; visual 2 adults, a pair seen concurrently at tree cavity, bringing food into a cavity filled with nestlings (can hear continuous food-begging nestlings within cavity) in a ponderosa pine snag at top of Mill Cr canyon  Visual of a 4th adult photographed with food in bill and part of a front yard pair and a photograph of it with mate by Stewart Fletcher ---- It is NOT a daggetti subspecies by May 29, 2023 confirmation from woodpecker specialist, Stephen Shunk, who shares, "CJ, I don't think you can call that bird a daggetti.  The southern daggetti subspecies shows at least SOME semblance of a white supercilium, and it is absent in this bird. There is no noticeable white above the eye.   The bigger issue here is that introgression occurs between the two subspecies--we know this--and since daggetti is more prone to movement, the intergrades may also be more prone to wandering than the pure S.r. ruber. With the exception of far western individuals, IDing RBSA to subspecies in Oregon is very problematic, especially on the eastern slope of the Cascades; this bird was near the OR/WA border and east of the Cascades. The prudent thing is to record this bird as RBSA, with no subspecies distinction.   The compulsion to assign an ID to birds gets in the way of our understanding and appreciation of their genetics, including systematics and taxonomy. We have to appreciate the complicated situation that occurs with RNSA and RBSA in the West, especially in the Cascades. Many hybrids and intergrades occur here, and it may take DNA to narrow an ID to species, let alone subspecies."  Stephen Shunk - steve@paradisebirding.com Paradise Birding & Naturalist Journeys www.paradisebirding.com & www.naturalistjourneys.com +1-541-408-1753  Photographs:  Linda Steider and Stewart Fletcher

Found by Ken Murphey earlier this week.  The bird has stayed in the general location preferring sap from holes drilled into a Gooding's Willow along the Santa Cruz river effluent.  The bird has been seen by many observers and I am sure it has been scrutinized for any hybridization.  In the field I began to worry that I was seeing some light flecking of black feathers loosely in the breast, but only while viewing the bird while it was in the shade.  When the bird is in the sun the breast appears bright red with no black feathers.  I also like the amount of red in the face specifically through the moustacial stripe.  I don't see many RBSAs hardly ever so I had to do some extra research at home and now am feeling better about calling it pure.  The bird was totally silent the whole time, even while being harassed by local Gila Woodpeckers.

At first quiet, well, besides the aircraft and traffic noise. I listened carefully for tapping, and hearing it, zeroed in. As I moved under the source they became very active and vocal with each other, staying close and interacting as the both foraged for insects and worked on some of their sap wells. There are many favored treed around the part that are riddled with sap wells. I am curious what makes one tree preferred over the others. Appear to be same species of eucalyptus. There is a very big euc in the center of the park that has wells all over it. But this morning I found them here: 32.786677, -117.195533 (Accuracy: 16 ft). I had wanted to see a sapsucker this winter and forgot about checking this park for them, until Eric and Nancy’s recent post reminded me.  32.78668,-117.19553

Nice to share the bounty :-)

Got a couple photos although light not real good.  Bird stayed in same location for 15 minutes we were there.  Lifer. All reddish head and neck eliminating Red-naped and Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers.  But head and neck not bright eliminating Red-headed Woodpecker.  Has white wing patches and and short moustacial stripe of this species.  Can't see large white wing patch or white rump. Continuing, at GPS coordinates in W. Egelhoff's eBird report from last weekend. First heard loud drumming on the large dead cottonwood (about 9:30 a.m) then it moved to the large hackberry where it spent the next half hour attending dripping sapsucker wells and creating new ones. Head red with red extending down onto breast. Black smudgy patch on the auriculars and black lores. Didn't appear to have any black on the back of the head. Short white moustachial stripe, indicating northern subspecies, but back had two rows of white markings, no apparent yellow or gold spots, indicating southern subspecies. Intergrade?

**First Colorado State Record** Pure adult bird with completely red head except white at the base of the bill. Red spilling onto breast as well, and wings mostly black except the white bar through the secondary and median coverts, and outer primaries lightly barred. Narrow faint column of small goldenish (grayish?) barring on the back, and some white at the tips of the tertial feathers. Belly very yellow with faint zigzag pattern throughout. Notice also the very small white spots (as opposed to wider white stripes in the southern ssp or Red-naped) on the inner side of the two central rectrices. This close examination of entire head, nape, wing coverts, and tail feathers suggests pure adult ruber ssp, with absolutely no marks or signs indicating Red-naped ancestry. Accepted by the CBRC.

Media notes: back of head, nape, and back pattern with some white spotting described as variable in Birds of North America Online.
Observation Details: sapsucker with complete red head except for black auricular patches and short white malar with red continuing below nape and onto breast where it is defined from yellow breast. Black back with faint white streaks and large white wing patch. Separated from southern subspecies, daggetti, by the shorter white malar (see photos). Sexes not separable in field. Found on 21 December 2017 by David Tonnessen who was surveying for sapsuckers in non-native conifers in the area.

I never would have guessed RB Sapsucker young look like this -"  Tom M.: "Thanks for getting back to me!  Yes, the red is brownish on the juvenile - I had to look up a juvenile Williamson's because I don't recall ever seeing one and they look pretty much like adults."  me: "Yeah, I looked in Steve Shunk's new woodpecker book,  and he has zero photos of juv male WISA,  and the 2 photos of juv RBSA both show reddish wash, though otherwise look like my photoed bird. So thanks for helping me, and I'll just cont. to photo what woodpeckers I find and in future hope also to get some photos of young WISA to study."  Tom M.: "Look in the "big" Sibley (not the western), he has drawings of both juv male & female.  The juvenile male looks like an adult except for the throat is white instead of red and the black and white isn't quite so striking. You're more than welcome to eBird on "my" side of the crest - it's always great to get checklists from the high Cascades!"

Sighted right by an access point between Sudden Valley Gate 5 and the Lookout Mountain Forest Preserve. I Heard this individual calling before I saw it peek out from the left (from my perspective) side of the base of a nearby Douglas Fir. It continued calling and eyeing me as it made its way around the base of the trunk, creeping slightly upward until it was a couple of feet of the ground and tapping on the bark. Once the bird had made it to the right (from my perspective) side of the trunk of the fir, I repositioned to the same side of the tree as the bird, and was able to get significantly closer to it. At this point, the bird hopped onto a nearby sapling, facing me, and peeked over the side of the sapling at me. I left shortly after to leave the bird to its affairs.

Sphyrapicus r. ruber differs from daggetti mainly in its brighter red head (in fresh plumage scarlet rather than crimson), less extensive white head stripe, and smaller yellow-tinged spots on the back."

Adult 'Southern'. Woodpecker with a red on head and partly down chest, white stripe along leading edge of wing (when folded), and black back with brown and white pattern. Pattern on back converged at the base of the neck and end of wings - widened down the middle of the back. Patterned sides with a light yellow stomach. Barred inner tail feathers and solid black outer tail feathers. Gray bill with cream tufts on either side. Slight white line extending back diagonally back from tufts net to bill down to its neck and along the shoulder. Black eye. Found in the mesquite just behind the yellow fire hydrant at the pull in to the parking area by the baseball fields and volleyball courts. At the SW corner of the tennis courts. Bird was still most of the time and quiet.

Continuing bird that had gone unreported since December 24th (I believe).  At 10:30am I noticed a woodpecker moving high in one of the two *very* large (mostly dead) Cottonwoods at the site (where I believe the bird had been originally found). It then flew overhead to a tree on the eastern hillside before finally flying to and hanging out in the large dead looking fruit tree immediately adjacent to the trail. All this time it was giving a loud, thin "Merrrrrrr" call. Approximately the same size as a Red-naped or Yellow-bellied Sapsucker. Cherry red head, bib, and breast with blackish (dusky) lores and limited bit in the auriculars. Longish silvery bill. Limited white moustachial mark seems less extensive than might be expected for the "daggetti" subspecies. Lemony-yellow wash to the underparts with dusky streaking down either flank. Upperparts black with two rows of yellowish spotting running down the back. Conspicuous white wing patches visible both in flight and when wings were folded. No clear indicators of any Red-naped Sapsucker ancestry. Seen at the coordinates: 32.837183, -108.604162

Continuing.   This sapsucker is very interesting … I see a ruber head, being red-helmeted with red bleeding over the white border, and the red being fairly bright. However, I see a daggetti’s excessive back patterning and the back spots being more off-white vs yellow like on a ruber. Another interesting feature, is that the red from its head bleeds past its nape and onto its upper back. I am fascinated by this subject, and feedback is ways appreciated!!  0919 -  Observed working a Tipu approx. here (33.7065371, -118.0028552) by Loren’s Ditch. Silent and solo.  Update (2/3) : Tom W and I had a discussion, confirming this subspecies as the "daggetti" subspecies. Thank you, Tom, for your wonderful insight into this interesting character!! :))
